Australia

[Murray Valley encephalitis is endemic in New Guinea and in parts of
Australia. The disease is carried by culicine mosquitoes. _Culex
annulirostris_ is a key vector in transmission to man, and other
species play a role in transmission among animal reservoirs. This is
the 1st report of the isolation of Murray Valley encephalitis virus
(MVEV) from mosquitoes in NSW. Infection with MVEV is often
subclinical and perhaps only one in 800-1000 or fewer of those
infected will go on to develop a clinically significant disease. For
others, the symptoms can range from mild to severe. The incubation
period is 7-28 days and symptoms almost invariably include fever;
headache nausea and vomiting are common. Of those who show clinically
significant disease, 25 percent have died and 25-50 percent show
permanent neurological damage. When encephalitis develops, brain
dysfunction may be experienced after a few days with lethargy,
irritability, drowsiness, confusion, convulsions, and fits; neck
stiffness can be expected, and both coma and death may ensue.

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map of Australia is available at
<http://healthmap.org/promed?v=-25.7,134.5,4>, showing the boundaries
and geography of New South Wales. - Mod.CP

This finding is a warning that MVE virus is circulating in the NSW
area. Although no human cases have been found in NSW this century,
NSW was the site of one of the 1st 4 isolations of MVE virus in 1951.
MVE is thought to be the same as Australian X disease, which caused
an epidemic in NSW in 1918. In 1974, the 1st 8 cases of what became a
big epidemic were recorded from NSW, but no cases have been reported
from there since then.

Reference
---------
Marshall ID 2001: Murray Valley encephalitis. In Service MW [ed.] The
Encyclopedia of Arthropod-transmitted Infections. CABI Publishing,
UK. - Mod.JW]
